\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Evaluating class naming conventions**\\\\n\\\\nI need to consider the guideline about not using `$` in test class names, which applies to inner or anonymous classes. However, it doesn't seem to restrict nested helper classes, as existing Java code likely includes them. If I pass a nested helper to Class.forName, the dynamic name will contain `$`, which isn't a test class name. It might be safer to use package-private helper classes, but I must be cautious about potential conflicts with public top-level instructions. I'll also check if they lack the @Test annotation, which could indicate they’re viewed differently by checkstyle.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Examining Spring's bean instantiation**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about Spring registering as the primary source and trying to instantiate a package-private bean class. It might be accessible using reflection with setAccessible, but in native image, the metadata could cause issues with agent records. During AOT generation, it seems like it might generate source code that references `org_springframework_boot.spring_boot.StringArgsAotApplication`, assuming the generated class is in the same package as the main application. This could allow access to package-private classes. If it’s referring to the no-arg constructor, that’s fine since the generated source isn’t compiled.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_h5TG61dFnCSO2b2c6mLfKBT1|fc_02910d8b2c0c8ff6016a24bf5e59f08190aa8e8e195d674d20\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"rg -n \\\"spring-context|spring-core\\\" ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.springframework.boot/spring-boot/4.0.6 -g '*.pom' || true\", \"timeout\": 20}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"oca/gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 450, \"output\": 1468, \"cacheRead\": 32768, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 34686, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"out